event: step.delta
data: {"index":6,"delta":{"content":{"text":"**Planning a Retro Website**\n\nI'm currently focused on the HTML page elements, figuring out what content will make the page extremely complete and authentic. I'm exploring potential file additions, and the possibility of adding a file to the page called `geocities`. Before I work out the files for the page, I need to find some excellent URLs for GIFs, or create some placeholders to look retro. I'm excited to make a truly beautiful retro site!\n\n\n","type":"text"},"type":"thought_summary"},"event_type":"step.delta"}

event: step.delta
data: {"index":6,"delta":{"content":{"text":"**Designing the Directory Structure**\n\nI've decided to create a directory, `/geocities`, to house the masterpiece, starting with an `index.html` file. I'm focusing on authentic early-web design, planning a starfield background, possibly with a GIF, or a CSS-based alternative. I'm gathering classic \"under construction\" GIFs, aiming for stable URLs from GeoCities archives. I'll search for stable retro image URLs now.\n\n\n","type":"text"},"type":"thought_summary"},"event_type":"step.delta"}

event: step.delta
data: {"index":6,"delta":{"content":{"text":"**Locating Stable Retro URLs**\n\nI am now sourcing reliable, existing URLs for classic animated GIFs, prioritizing those known to be stable or archived. I've found a few promising candidates: the dancing baby, dancing banana, envelope GIFs, and Netscape and Internet Explorer badges, all hosted on reliable servers like the Wayback Machine or Wikimedia Commons. My goal is to use these GIFs.\n\n\n","type":"text"},"type":"thought_summary"},"event_type":"step.delta"}

